  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research, focusing on a broadly generalizable stabilization strategy for sarbecovirus fusion machinery vaccines, has made significant contributions to the field, as evidenced by its 23 citations in the open academic discourse and the active engagement that follows its subsequent publication.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"A broadly generalizable stabilization strategy for sarbecovirus fusion machinery vaccines\" has successfully transitioned to a peer-reviewed publication, highlighting its effective contribution to the understanding of vaccine development strategies relevant to sarbecoviruses. This journey has culminated in 18 citations of the formally published version, underscoring the work's robust academic influence.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research is backed by notable institutions, including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, enhancing its credibility and reach across the scientific community. The geographic diversity of the citing countries, which include the United States, Italy, and South Africa, points to a wide recognition of the importance of this work globally.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the lack of social media discourse on platforms such as Reddit and Wikipedia, the drawn attention indicated by 22 online mentions reflects ongoing interest and engagement within the academic community. The fact that there have been a total of 25 instances of downstream reuse further indicates that the materials and findings from this research have enabled subsequent studies, showcasing their utility and importance.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Through the early sharing of the preprint, the authors exemplified a commitment to open science, arguably facilitating immediate community engagement and dialogue on descendent works before formal publication. Overall, this article not only contributes foundational knowledge to vaccine methodologies but also serves as a model of effective and timely scientific communication within an impactful research domain.</p>",
